- platform/browser-extension/src/side-panel/styles.css (dark theme variables in .dark block, lines 77-109)
- docs/app/global.css (dark theme variables in .dark block, lines 62-83)

Context:
The dark theme values must stay in sync between the side panel and docs site. The CLAUDE.md for both projects states: 'The side panel theme (styles.css) and the docs theme (docs/app/global.css) share the same design system. The core tokens must stay in sync.'

Current dark theme values (both files identical):
```css
.dark {
  --background: #1a1a1a;
  --foreground: #f5f5f5;
  --card: #242424;
  --card-foreground: #f5f5f5;
  --primary: #ffdb33;
  --primary-hover: #ffcc00;
  --primary-foreground: #000;
  --secondary: #3a3a3a;
  --secondary-hover: #4a4a4a;
  --secondary-foreground: #f5f5f5;
  --muted: #3f3f46;
  --muted-foreground: #a0a0a0;
  --accent: #fae583;
  --accent-foreground: #000;
  --destructive: #e63946;
  --destructive-foreground: #fff;
  --success: #22c55e;
  --success-foreground: #000;
  --border: #5c5c5c;
}
```

Note: The docs global.css does NOT have --secondary-hover, --success, or --success-foreground tokens. It also has extra --code-bg, --code-fg, --inline-code-bg, --inline-code-fg tokens that the side panel doesn't have. Only change the shared tokens.

The problem: --border (#5c5c5c) is too close to --card (#242424) and --background (#1a1a1a). The flat offset shadow `4px 4px 0 0 var(--border)` — which is the signature retro look — becomes nearly invisible. Everything sits in a narrow dark-gray tonal range.

Recommended new values:
```css
.dark {
  --background: #111111;   /* was #1a1a1a — deeper black for backdrop */
  --card: #1c1c1c;         /* was #242424 — slightly darker for better shadow contrast */
  --border: #777777;       /* was #5c5c5c — brighter for crisp edges and visible shadows */
  --muted: #333333;        /* was #3f3f46 — darker muted for better hierarchy */
  --secondary: #333333;    /* was #3a3a3a — track with muted */
  --secondary-hover: #444444; /* was #4a4a4a */
}
```

These changes restore high contrast: the border (#777) against card (#1c1c1c) has a delta of ~97 in luminance, compared to the current delta of ~42. The shadow becomes clearly visible.

Verification approach: After making the changes, run `npm run storybook:build` in platform/browser-extension/ to verify the Storybook compiles. Then visually verify in Storybook by switching to dark mode. The cards should have clearly visible offset shadows and crisp borders.

Constraints:
- Both files MUST have identical values for all shared tokens (--background, --foreground, --card, --card-foreground, --primary, --primary-hover, --primary-foreground, --secondary, --secondary-foreground, --muted, --muted-foreground, --accent, --accent-foreground, --destructive, --destructive-foreground, --border)
- Do NOT change any :root (light theme) values
- Do NOT change --primary or --primary-foreground in dark mode (yellow stays yellow)
- Do NOT change --foreground (#f5f5f5) or --card-foreground (#f5f5f5)
- Do NOT change the docs-only tokens (--code-bg, --code-fg, --inline-code-bg, --inline-code-fg) unless they need adjustment for the new background
- Do NOT change the side-panel-only tokens (--success, --success-foreground, --secondary-hover) in the docs file since docs doesn't have them
- Verify the dark avatar palette colors (--avatar-0 through --avatar-9) still look readable against the new --card value. If any look too dark, brighten them slightly.
- The exact hex values above are recommendations — use your judgment to find values that look right. The key constraint is: border must be significantly brighter, background must be deeper, and the shadow must be clearly visible.

Files:
- platform/browser-extension/src/side-panel/styles.css (animation keyframes and classes, lines 144-169)

Context:
The current animations in styles.css:
```css
@keyframes activity-border-flash {
  0%,
  100% {
    border-color: var(--primary);
  }
  50% {
    border-color: var(--border);
  }
}

.animate-activity-border-flash {
  animation: activity-border-flash 0.4s ease-in-out infinite;
}

@keyframes activity-border-fade-out {
  from {
    border-color: var(--primary);
  }
  to {
    border-color: var(--border);
  }
}

.animate-activity-border-fade-out {
  animation: activity-border-fade-out 0.5s ease-out forwards;
}
```

The problem: The browser interpolates between --primary (#ffdb33, yellow) and --border (#000000, black) in sRGB color space. The midpoint of sRGB interpolation between yellow and black is approximately #7f6e1a — a muddy dark olive/brown. This 'third color' appears during every frame of the transition and looks jarring.

In dark mode it's similar: interpolating between #ffdb33 (yellow) and #5c5c5c (gray, or #777777 after US-002) produces a desaturated yellowish-gray in mid-transition frames.

Changes:

1. Replace the flash animation with a stepped binary blink (no interpolation):
```css
@keyframes activity-border-flash {
  0%, 49.9% {
    border-color: var(--primary);
  }
  50%, 100% {
    border-color: var(--border);
  }
}

.animate-activity-border-flash {
  animation: activity-border-flash 0.6s steps(1) infinite;
}
```

The `steps(1)` timing function means there is exactly one step per keyframe interval — the border color snaps instantly between yellow and border with zero interpolation. The duration is slightly longer (0.6s vs 0.4s) because binary blinks at high speed feel aggressive.

Alternatively, the keyframe split at 49.9%/50% can be simplified since `steps(1)` already prevents interpolation. The simpler form:
```css
@keyframes activity-border-flash {
  0%, 50% {
    border-color: var(--primary);
  }
  50.01%, 100% {
    border-color: var(--border);
  }
}
```

Either approach works — the key is that `steps(1)` on the animation property eliminates all interpolation.

2. For the fade-out animation, the approach is different because a binary snap from yellow to border at the end would feel abrupt. Instead, fade through opacity rather than color:
```css
@keyframes activity-border-fade-out {
  from {
    border-color: var(--primary);
    opacity: 1;
  }
  to {
    border-color: var(--primary);
    opacity: 0.6;
  }
}
```

Wait — that changes the entire element's opacity, not just the border. A better approach: since the fade-out is only 0.5s and goes from yellow to the resting border color, the muddy middle frame is less noticeable because it flashes by quickly. But to fully avoid it, we can use a two-stage approach:
```css
@keyframes activity-border-fade-out {
  0% {
    border-color: var(--primary);
  }
  70% {
    border-color: var(--primary);
  }
  100% {
    border-color: var(--border);
  }
}

.animate-activity-border-fade-out {
  animation: activity-border-fade-out 0.5s ease-out forwards;
}
```

This holds yellow for 70% of the duration, then quickly transitions to border in the last 30% (150ms). The brief transition window means the muddy intermediate is barely visible — much less noticeable than the current 500ms linear transition.

Alternatively, use `steps(1, end)` for a hard snap at the very end:
```css
@keyframes activity-border-fade-out {
  0%, 80% {
    border-color: var(--primary);
  }
  100% {
    border-color: var(--border);
  }
}

.animate-activity-border-fade-out {
  animation: activity-border-fade-out 0.4s steps(2, end) forwards;
}
```

Use your judgment to pick the approach that looks best. The key requirement is: no visible muddy olive/brown color during the flash animation, and minimal muddy color during the fade-out.

Constraints:
- Do NOT modify PluginIcon.tsx or ToolIcon.tsx — only the CSS animation definitions in styles.css
- Do NOT change the animation class names (.animate-activity-border-flash, .animate-activity-border-fade-out) — components reference them by name
- Do NOT add new CSS variables for this — use the existing --primary and --border
- The stepped blink should still feel like an 'active' indicator — not too fast (seizure-inducing) and not too slow (looks broken). 0.5-0.7s per cycle is the sweet spot.
- Test in both light and dark mode mentally: light mode blinks between yellow and black, dark mode blinks between yellow and the new --border value from US-002
